Brief country context:

The United States is a federal republic located in North America. It is made up of 50 states and the District of Columbia.
The country has a population of approximately 331 million people.
The United States has a diverse population, with people from many different ethnic, racial, and cultural backgrounds.

Language of instruction:
The official language of the United States is English.
However, many schools also offer instruction in languages such as Spanish, Mandarin, and French.

Features of K-12 education system:
The education system in the United States is primarily administered by the individual states.
Each state sets its own curriculum standards and graduation requirements.
Public education is free and compulsory for children between the ages of 6 and 17.
Private schools and homeschooling are also options for families.
The K-12 education system includes primary (elementary) and secondary (high) school education.

Education issue of concern:
One of the biggest education issues in the United States is the achievement gap between students from different socioeconomic backgrounds.
Studies have shown that students from low-income families tend to have lower academic achievement and graduation rates than their more affluent peers.

Key education policies and/or programs addressing the issue:
The No Child Left Behind Act (NCLB) was passed in 2001 with the goal of closing the achievement gap and increasing accountability for schools and teachers.
The Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA) was passed in 2015 as a replacement for NCLB, with a focus on states and local communities having more control over education policy.
Title I funding provides financial assistance to schools with a high percentage of students from low-income families.
The Head Start program provides comprehensive early childhood education, health, and nutrition services to low-income children and families.
The National School Lunch Program provides free or low-cost meals to students from low-income families.

